# PeerPoint Backend — Project Rules & Context

Read this file fully before making any change. It exists so that any agent working
on this codebase — including ones with no memory of prior sessions — inherits the
decisions already made here, instead of rediscovering, contradicting, or "fixing"
something that was deliberate.

---

## 1. What this project actually is

PeerPoint is a peer-counselling platform being built for Strathmore University's
Mental Health Club. **This is a real product for long-term production use, not a
class assignment or demo.** It will be used by real students, real peer
counsellors, and real administrators, likely for years. The Mental Health Club
president is an actual stakeholder/client for product decisions, not a grading
rubric.

Treat every decision — schema design, endpoint design, error handling, naming —
the way an experienced engineering team would when building something they're
accountable for maintaining long after this semester ends. Favor correctness,
auditability, and maintainability over the fastest thing that makes a demo work.

The frontend was built first, deliberately, as a way of surfacing real requirements
before backend work began. A full requirements audit derived from that frontend
lives at `frontend_audit.md` — read it before doing any schema or endpoint
work, since it is the source of truth for what the backend needs to support.

**The audit describes the frontend's needs as of when it was generated. This file
describes what the backend actually has and has decided. Where the two disagree,
this file wins for backend implementation decisions — flag the conflict rather
than silently picking one.**

