## 3. Current actual state of the backend (read this before assuming anything)

Be precise about what exists vs. what's planned — do not assume a planned change
has already happened, and do not assume something not yet built is out of scope
just because it isn't there yet.

**Already built and verified (do not casually rewrite):**
- Authentication and role-based access control — complete, verified end-to-end in
  Swagger UI. This includes registration, login, and JWT issuance.
- **`session_requests` is the canonical session entity.** All session reads and
  writes go through the `session_requests` table (integer `id`). The legacy
  `CounsellingSession` / `sessions` table and string S-1001-style IDs were
  dropped in migration `004_drop_sessions` — do not reintroduce them.
- A `require_active_counsellor` dependency that checks both role and
  verification status before allowing counsellor-only actions.


ARCHITECTURE DECISION

The frontend audit references a legacy single-role model
(users.role).

This is retained in the audit for historical accuracy.

Authorization should migrate to user_roles
as described in the User Roles ADR below.

When implementing authorization features,
follow the user_roles design documented here,
not the legacy single-role assumptions in the audit.
**Current role model (IMPORTANT — about to change, but hasn't yet):**
- The backend currently uses a **single `role` enum column on `users`**
  (`student | counsellor | admin`). Promotion today would mean overwriting this
  value.
- **This is a known, deliberate, planned-but-not-yet-executed change.** The
  target architecture (already decided, not up for debate) replaces this with a
  `user_roles` join table supporting multiple, independently granted/revoked
  roles per user — see Section 4. **Do not build new scaffolding that assumes
  the single-role model is permanent.** If you are scaffolding something that
  touches authorization and the `user_roles` migration hasn't landed yet,
  scaffold it in a way that will be easy to adapt (e.g. don't hardcode
  `user.role ==` checks deep in business logic if you can reasonably route them
  through a single dependency/helper instead) — but do not attempt the
  migration yourself unless that is explicitly the task you were given.

**Not yet built (do not assume these exist):**
- The `user_roles` table and migration.
- Full scaffolding completion across all documented endpoints/models in the
  audit — this is in progress, not finished.

